article.description: Catchings closing in on team's career rebound mark
article.headline: Storm plays without injured Jackson
article.linkText: House afire: Fever wins 10th straight at home
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- In just her second WNBA season, Tamika
Catchings already is Indiana's career leader in rebounding and is
rapidly closing in on the franchise record for points.

Catchings had 20 points, seven rebounds and a career-high seven
assists in the Fever's 79-70 victory over the Seattle Storm on
Saturday night. It was the 10th consecutive victory at Conseco
Fieldhouse for the Fever, who haven't lost here since last July 19.

Catchings became the second player in Fever history to top 800
points and is just 46 short of the franchise record of 852 set by
Rita Williams in 2000-02. Her fifth rebound Saturday broke the
franchise mark of 372 set by Olympia Scott-Richardson.

All of this has taken last year's WNBA rookie of the year just
44 games.

"I think it is pretty incredible because she's an incredible
player, so I'm not surprised," said Indiana coach Nell Fortner,
who picked the former Tennessee star third in the 2001 draft and
then had to wait a year while she recuperated from a knee injury.

Catchings had plenty of help. Four Indiana starters finished in
double figures. Natalie Williams had 18 points, Kristen Rasmussen
14 and Niele Ivey 12 -- all on 3-pointers.

"Our ball movement was really good," Fortner said. "When we
move the ball, reverse it, look for the best shot on the floor
we're really a pretty good team."

Indiana (7-5) shot 50 percent and hit 50 percent of its 3-point
attempts.

"Natalie Williams was pretty tough down inside. We ran some
things to get her the ball in the paint. We scored 42 points in the
paint. That gets me excited as a coach," Fortner said.

The Storm (7-6) played without league scoring leader Lauren
Jackson, who did not dress after injuring her right foot in
Seattle's 71-59 victory at Cleveland on Friday.

"It definitely affected the team, playing without our
superstar," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "It changes the
defense and offensive sets, totally."

Sandy Brondello made up for the absence of Jackson's 19.1
scoring average by setting a franchise record with 19 points in the
first half.

Brondello's 8-of-9 shooting effort, including three 3-pointers
without a miss, gave the Storm a 43-42 halftime advantage. But the
Fever denied her the ball in the second half when she went
scoreless and missed the only two shots she attempted.

"We had a nice little talk about that at halftime. We just
weren't going to give that up again. We just turned up the
defensive pressure on her," Fortner said. "She was touching the
ball too easy in the first half. We had to keep the ball out of her
hands, or we had to affect her more defensively and I thought Nikki
McCray did a great job of that."

The Storm, who shot 51 percent from the field, also had four
players in double figures. Simone Edwards had 14, Kamila Vodichkova
12 and Sue Bird 11.

Indiana broke a 49-49 deadlock and took the lead for good on a
short jump shot by Catchings. The Fever's biggest lead was 73-59.
